 another.' b'traditionally, they have used pictures, words, demonstrations,' b'music and dance to communicate imagery. however, expressing' b'complex notions such as god and infinity or a seemingly well' b'defined concept such as a flower can present challenges which far' b'exceed their technical skills.' b'' b'the explosive use of computers as visualization and expression' b'tools has compounded this problem. in hypermedia, multimedia and' b'virtual reality systems vast amounts of information confront the' b'observer or participant. wading through a multitude of' b'simultaneous images and sounds in possibly unfamiliar' b'representions, a confounded user asks: "what does it all mean?"' b'' b'since image construction, transmission, reception, decipherment and' b'ultimate understanding are complex tasks, strongly influenced by' b'physiology, education and culture; and, since electronic media' b'radically amplify each processing step, then we, as electronic' b'communicators, must determine the fundamental paradigms for' b'composing imagery for understanding.' b'' b'therefore, the purpose of this conference is to bring together a' b'breadth of disciplines, including, but not limited to, the' b'physical, biological and computational sciences, technology, art,' b'psychology, philosophy, and education, in order to define and' b'discuss the issues essential to image understanding within the' b'computer graphics context.' b'' b'' b'featured speakers include:' b'' b'psychology/perception:' b'marc de may, university of ghent' b'beverly j. jones, university of oregon' b'barbara tversky, standfor university' b'michael j. shiffer, mit' b'tom hubbard, ohio state university' b'image analysis:' b'a. ravishankar rao, ibm watson research center' b'nalini bhusan, smith college' b'xiaopin hu, university of illinois' b'narenda ahuja, university of illinois' b'les m. sztander, university of toledo' b'design:' b'mark bajuk, university of illinois' b'alyce kaprow, mit' b'text:' b'xia lin, p